Both Kielhorn and Mirashi observe that in l1 °atirotra was corrected to °atirātra. I accept this, though in the rubbing only a clear o mātrā is visible. 
--><!-- 
There are a couple of marks at the end of l1, looking like a short dash after ti, followed by what seems to be a subscript halanta M. Both may be random. Alternatively, the dash may be a space filler (there being some room left at the end, but apparently not enough for sa); the halanta M possibly a correction for mma in the next line, correcting vākāṭakānāmma to vākāṭakānāM ma. 
--><!-- 
Of the va preceding the hole in l4, only the top and left strokes of the boxhead are visible; the rest was, as Kielhorn notes, either never engraved or has been completely effaced. If the former, then perhaps the engraver realised after starting the character that the hole was too close and wanted to inscribe it after the hole but then forgot. 
--><!-- 
Kielhorn and Mirashi print the visarga in l9 as supplied; I think it is in fact there as a later addition, looking like a pair of commas (rather than dots) between nai and sa, a bit above and below where a regular visarga's points would be. 
--><!-- 
In l13 both Kielhorn and Mirashi read ārammi, but the character in question seems to be mb, not mm (for which compare e.g. l11). Mirashi_1963:44 notes that Hira Lal (in Inscriptions in C P and Berar) identifies Ārammi as Ārvī, the head of a tehsil in Wardha district. Mirashi finds this unsatisfactory, and also notes that Ārammi is also mentioned in the Pandhurna plates (IN00171). There the reding is clearly mmi in one instance (IN00171:29) and very unclear in another instance (IN00171:26). 
--><!-- 
The visarga of °kr̥tāḥ in l14 is very strange, it looks like a subscript halanta character. 
--></p>
